string-input-393:1601:329:446.description:
Pattern selecting the second group of columns. The columns in this group will be matched with columns from the first group using the iterator. The iterator is defined similarly to the pattern in group 1. 
Example: single column "sector_demand_.*", multiple columns "sector_variable_(.*)\[.*"

This pattern can also optionally include a second iterator for combining each column from the first group with multiple columns from the second group.
Example: "sector_variable_(.*)_(.*)\[.*"

Note that these patterns can also be used to identify flow variables. They work exactly the same, flow variables matching the name will be transformed into columns in the data (with the same value for every row).

Only in the Python version, a named regex group can be used to explicitly identify the iterator if it's not the first group. The pattern is "sector_variable_(.*)_(?P<i>.*)\[.*". This give the name "i" (as in iterator) to the second group. The naming of the resulting variable is not affected by this (i.e. it's still the iterator,, then the second group of the first pattern, then the second group of the second pattern.

string-input-393:1601:329:445.description:
Pattern selecting the first group of columns. The resulting columns will be appended with the iterator, which is a Regex capture group embedded in the pattern. 
Example: "sector_variable_(.*)\[.*" to use the last item before the unit as the iterator. 

Note that these patterns can also be used to identify flow variables. They work exactly the same, flow variables matching the name will be transformed into columns in the data (with the same value for every row).

string-input-393:1602:322:445.description:
Pattern selecting the first group of columns. The resulting columns will be appended with the iterator, which is a Regex capture group embedded in the pattern. 
Example: "sector_variable_(.*)\[.*" to use the last item before the unit as the iterator. 

Note that these patterns can also be used to identify flow variables. They work exactly the same, flow variables matching the name will be transformed into columns in the data (with the same value for every row).

string-input-393:1602:322:446.description:
Pattern selecting the second group of columns. The columns in this group will be matched with columns from the first group using the iterator. The iterator is defined similarly to the pattern in group 1. 
Example: single column "sector_demand_.*", multiple columns "sector_variable_(.*)\[.*"

This pattern can also optionally include a second iterator for combining each column from the first group with multiple columns from the second group.
Example: "sector_variable_(.*)_(.*)\[.*"

Note that these patterns can also be used to identify flow variables. They work exactly the same, flow variables matching the name will be transformed into columns in the data (with the same value for every row).

Only in the Python version, a named regex group can be used to explicitly identify the iterator if it's not the first group. The pattern is "sector_variable_(.*)_(?P<i>.*)\[.*". This give the name "i" (as in iterator) to the second group. The naming of the resulting variable is not affected by this (i.e. it's still the iterator,, then the second group of the first pattern, then the second group of the second pattern.

string-input-393:1584:322:445.description:
Pattern selecting the first group of columns. The resulting columns will be appended with the iterator, which is a Regex capture group embedded in the pattern. 
Example: "sector_variable_(.*)\[.*" to use the last item before the unit as the iterator. 

Note that these patterns can also be used to identify flow variables. They work exactly the same, flow variables matching the name will be transformed into columns in the data (with the same value for every row).

string-input-393:1584:322:446.description:
Pattern selecting the second group of columns. The columns in this group will be matched with columns from the first group using the iterator. The iterator is defined similarly to the pattern in group 1. 
Example: single column "sector_demand_.*", multiple columns "sector_variable_(.*)\[.*"

This pattern can also optionally include a second iterator for combining each column from the first group with multiple columns from the second group.
Example: "sector_variable_(.*)_(.*)\[.*"

Note that these patterns can also be used to identify flow variables. They work exactly the same, flow variables matching the name will be transformed into columns in the data (with the same value for every row).

Only in the Python version, a named regex group can be used to explicitly identify the iterator if it's not the first group. The pattern is "sector_variable_(.*)_(?P<i>.*)\[.*". This give the name "i" (as in iterator) to the second group. The naming of the resulting variable is not affected by this (i.e. it's still the iterator,, then the second group of the first pattern, then the second group of the second pattern.
